I&#39;m working on Big-O Notation for university, and I have some exercises to determine the Big-O and Time Complexity of a code snippet. The code snippet below is what I need to determine the Big-O Notation for:

```
for(int i = 1; i &lt; n; i++){

    for(int j = 1; j &lt; 100; j++){

        System.out.println(&quot;Hello World&quot;);
    }
}

int k = 1;
while(k &lt; n){
    k = k * 2;
}
```

In my work through of the exercise, I determined the first two for loops to be O(n). The while loop is O(log&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;n). I added some comments to the code below to show my thinking.

```
for(int i = 1; i &lt; n; i++){ // This line loops until n times, thus O(n)

    for(int j = 1; j &lt; 100; j++){ // This line loops at a constant 100 times, thus O(1)

        System.out.println(&quot;Hello World&quot;); // This line prints once, O(1)
    }
}

// The notations above: O(n) + O(1) + O(1) = O(n)

int k = 1; // This line is used once, thus O(1)
while(k &lt; n){
    k = k * 2; // For every iteration, k is doubled. Thus, we need to find how many iterations, x, is needed until the condition is met. This is 2^x = n. Solve for n we get log2n. Therefore O(log2n) (the 2 would be a subscript)
}

// I&#39;m left with O(n) and O(log2n)
